    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Kripp plays games for a living, if he claims he didn't think being able to sell things back to a vendor at a good profit was wrong he's an idiot.  I do not think he is, so he knew it was wrong and abused it, then proceeded to show 4k or so more people how to do it.<br />
<br />
People crying because they abused an exploit heavily are experiencing cognitive dissonance.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Except, he was just converting karma to gold, and merely found the most efficient way to do it. How are you supposed to know what threshold is &quot;exploiting&quot; and what isn't? I certainly wouldn't think that salvaging my old karma items is an exploit (nor would I think that vendoring back my old karma items is an exploit). In regards to cooking specifically, a lot of mats can only be bought with karma- is vendoring the final product produced with those items exploiting? Because that's exactly what he did.<br />
<br />
edit- Just to clarify, there are TWO separate issues here. The first, where most people were banned, was the karma weapon exploit. The second, which is specific to Krip, is that cooking mats are bought with karma (and then vendoring the result).</div>
