    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_530280">Injijo, the analogy would be more apt if the bar tender had left an open bottle of decent tequila out after serving you a drink, you took it and then started distributing drinks to other people at the bar. After being kicked out for a few days, but being allowed in with the promise that you wouldn't ****ing steal bottles that get briefly left out on the bar top...however, you then went on to scream bloody murder about how your RIGHTS or some other silly **** that isn't relevant to accepting services under a contract are being abridged.<br />
<br />
Fact of the matter is, ANet has to stop this **** as much to protect the economy for players as to maintain a predictable and normal economy for themselves so their business model works. They need to sell stuff in the store...a store that also allows you to purchase goods with in game currency--having a flooded economy makes that damned difficult.<br />
<br />
Was it perhaps a bit extreme in some cases? Certainly. But, apparently, they do not have the capacity to roll individual characters back (which seems dubious or, at the very least, unfortunate but it's the stated position) so this was certainly the better choice than letting it just fester.<br />
<br />
Let's not even say it's a bug. It honestly probably isn't. It's an obvious oversight. Any REASONABLE player could be expected to understand that. If you are not a reasonable player and cannot parse obvious, potentially systems-damaging oversights from quirks of game mechanics in a build, then that is unfortunate but leaves your stance somewhat irrelevant.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
