    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_530287">I gotta agree with Injijo on this - the onus should definitely be on the developers, not on the player base. Poor coding/mistakes are not the player's fault. They found something that works and they used it. That would be like a player using a specific ability that instead of doing 100% of weapon damage it did 10,000% due to a misplaced decimal in the code. Sure, when you all of a sudden one-shot mobs that you know you shouldn't be one-shotting you know something is screwed up but is it then your responsibility to not use that ability? I don't believe it is. I believe it's now the devs responsibility to fix the code. <br />
<br />
Or what if instead of 5 karma, the items cost 100 karma. Some people would probably notice that things are a little off but is it now their fault if they make a profit? What if the cost was 1000 karma instead of 5000? Where is the point where the player is supposed to realize its an &quot;exploit&quot; as opposed to a &quot;discounted&quot; vendor?<br />
<br />
Using Diablo 3 as another example: they nerfed the amount of gold you get from pots because players found a way to make a lot of money doing easy &quot;pot&quot; runs. Should those players be banned because the devs didn't intend for players to do that? No, they fix what they think is wrong with the game and the players adapt. So then players would do quick Path of the Ancients runs for an easy treasure goblin. The devs didn't like it so they changed it. They didn't ban players who figured it out. They didn't take away the items they got. They realized they made in error and they fixed it.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
<br>
