		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Fact of the matter is, ANet has to stop this **** as much to protect the economy for players as to maintain a predictable and normal economy for themselves so their business model works. They need to sell stuff in the store...a store that also allows you to purchase goods with in game currency--having a flooded economy makes that damned difficult.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>I agree it needed to be stopped, so stop it.  The net gain from all the bannings is negative.  Change a few hundred or 1000 gold for a few hundred or 1000 upset(in varying degrees) players.  If most of the players were only banned 72 hours or less and the money wasn't erased, then the economy is still damaged.  So banning the players doesn't fix anything.  Of course, realistically the economy was not flooded, there was a larger influx than expected not a tsunami of gold left wreckage in its wake. <br />
<br />
<div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Was it perhaps a bit extreme in some cases? Certainly. But, apparently, they do not have the capacity to roll individual characters back (which seems dubious or, at the very least, unfortunate but it's the stated position) so this was certainly the better choice than letting it just fester.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Not being able to roll back accounts is almost certainly ********. If its not than that is simply another mistake ANet made for which they are punishing players . <br />
 <div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Let's not even say it's a bug. It honestly probably isn't. It's an obvious oversight. Any REASONABLE player could be expected to understand that. If you are not a reasonable player and cannot parse obvious, potentially systems-damaging oversights from quirks of game mechanics in a build, then that is unfortunate but leaves your stance somewhat irrelevant.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>I am a reasonable player.  But as Deser said, where is the line for a reasonable mistake versus a pre-designed better method/option?  Is this information defined for players anywhere?  No.  Should players be required to know what the devs define as reasonable?  No.  <br />
What a reasonable player should do is not important, what is important is what a reasonable dev/ MMO mgr should do.  A reasonable developer/ MMO manager will allow for players to push the boundaries of what the game is designed to do and certainly will not punish players for coding mistakes.  <br />
<br />
<div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
