  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">They were giving scaling bans depending on the level of advantage offender sought. Few people were actually perma-banned except for egregious offenders.<br />
<br />
*shrug* As was said, we're not going to see eye to eye on this, I take it. But, remember, you don't have a right to anything--it is a game and you agreed to play by their rules when you hopped on board. I'm more taken aback by yet again the level of entitlement the gaming community has shown on this.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Entitlement in this case is earned, through purchasing a product. People feel entitled to not be banned over using something that is in the game.  I've never said that ANET has not right to ban people. I'm saying it is bad business, generally shitty, and there are better obvious alternatives.</div>
